Introduction¶

In this project, I will be investigating a TMDB dataset, which is collection of movies released between 1960 upto 2015. This datset has information of movies, cast, genres, directors, budgets, revenues, proftis, ratings etc. I intend to do some EDA on the dataset and gather some information which can be put to future use. The set of questions I would like to explore will be keyed in later as I explore the dataset.

What can be infer for now from the dataset¶

a) There are some columns which may not be relevant like the id, imdb_id, tagline, keywords etc and also some columns which are duplicated,which we will remove to have a cleaner dataset¶

b) Since we have budget and revenue, we can use this to calculate profits, which is vital for any movie industry¶

c) Budget, revenue, profits will be assumed to be in USD as 'budget_adj' and 'revenue_adj' kind of give us the idea what the then calculated revenue and budgest means in terms of 2010 USD owing to inflation or devaluation of currency¶

d) The take way should be to find characteristics of movies that made handsome profits so that they are more reflective of viewer's taste, but again this is quite subjective as viewer's preference tend to change over generation.¶

Lets see what needs to be cleaned and wrangled for a cleaner view on the dataset¶

a) Remove irrelevant columns from the dataset. So these would be id', 'imdb_id', 'popularity', 'homepage', 'tagline', 'keywords', 'overview', 'budget_adj', 'revenue_adj'¶

b) Check for any duplicate rows and remove them¶

c) I could find there were many zeros in the budget and revenue column and this needs to be removed from the analyses. The need to be replaced with np.NaN so that we use can use the dropna to remove the associated rows¶

e) Check data types of different columns. The 'release_date' needs to be converted to a datetime format¶

f) Change column names accordingly. Here I am going to change the column - 'original_title' to 'movie_title' as a personal preference¶

# Using a function to split the entries in columns - cast, genres and production_companies

# Function returns the unique entries and count

def extract_columns_info(col_name):
    # Each column entry is a string and separate each using a '|'
    a = df[col_name].str.cat(sep='|')
    # Store it in a pandas series so that functions can apply. 
    b = pd.Series(a.split('|'))
    # Store the unique values for later user
    unique_entry = b.unique().tolist()
    # Count of the entries
    count = b.value_counts()
    # return the unique_count and total count
    return(unique_entry, count)

In [24]:
# For this we will use a function and to compare all charactertics, we will import all properties of the associated films by creating
# dataframes and concatenate them by column

def highestvzlowest(col):
    # Get the index of the highest value
    highest_index = df[col].idxmax()
    # Create a new dataframe with just one column with this
    highest_info = pd.DataFrame(df.loc[highest_index])
    
    # Similarly for lowest
    lowest_index = df[col].idxmin()
    # Create a new dataframe with just one column with this
    lowest_info = pd.DataFrame(df.loc[lowest_index])
    
    # Now concatenate both DF's by column
    combined_df = pd.concat([highest_info, lowest_info], axis=1)
    return combined_df

What percentage of movies starred by different casts made profits and who was the best¶

In [69]:
# Calling the function to extract the total count for column 'cast' for various actors/actresses
x = extract_columns_info('cast')[1]
# Only interested in actors/actresses who have starred in more than 27 movies, to focus on the more prominent ones
castm27 = x[x.values >27]

for i in castm27.index:
    a = df2[df2['cast'].str.contains(i) == True]
    # Profits > 0
    profit = a[a['profit'] > 0].count()['profit']
    # Total
    total = a['profit'].count()
    # Percentage
    percent = profit / total * 100
    #print(profit)
    #print(total)
    #print(percent)
    # Using string formatting
    print("Actor {} enacted in {} movies of which {} of the movies made profits".format(i, total, str(percent)))

Which month saw the highest number of release in a month¶

In [55]:
# Now that we know the number of release by year, let us look at the release by month. For this we will have to extract
# the month information for 'release_date' and then user groupby to group the releases per month.

# For this lets make the release data as the index so that the year, month or day information can be extracted easily

# Create a new DF - rel_date_df with index set as release_date
rel_date_df = df.set_index('release_date')
#rel_date_df.index.month
# Apply the group by on month - this can be extracted from <Dataframe>.index.month as the index is already in a 
# datetime format
# Get the count for the number of movies, this should basically be the same for all rows, and we will take count from
# column profit
count = rel_date_df.groupby(rel_date_df.index.month).profit.count()
#Converting the series into a Dataframe
movie_count_df = pd.DataFrame(count)
month_list =['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']

# A seaborn bar plot this time.
import seaborn as sns
#Syntax sns.barplot(x= <x_axis>, y = <y-axis>, data= <dataframe>);
sns_chart = sns.barplot(x= month_list, y = movie_count_df.profit, data= movie_count_df);
# Setting the labels for x-axis
sns_chart.set_xlabel('Month of the year', fontsize=20)
# Setting the font size for x-axis
sns_chart.set_xticklabels(month_list, fontsize=20)
# Setting the labels for y-axis
sns_chart.set_ylabel('Movie release count', fontsize=20)
# Setting the font size for y-axis
sns_chart.set_yticklabels(movie_count_df.profit, fontsize=20)
# Setting the overall fig size
sns_chart.figure.set_size_inches(15,10)
# Title and font size
sns_chart.axes.set_title('Movies count on their released months', fontsize=25)
plt.show();

# Now we will try to capture the profits by month

Conclusions¶

1) Highest number of films release are of the genre type -'Drama', follower by 'Comedy' and Thriller. In terms of percentage - Drama-17%, Comedy-13.2%, Thriller-11.7%, Action-10.5% and so on.

2) Steven Spielsberg had the highest number of movie releases at 28 , followed by Clint Eastwood at 24 and Ridely Scott at 21. In terms of percentage Steven Spielsberg -7.3% as compared to other what have directed released movies more than 11.

3) In terms of the number of casts - Robert De Niro starred in 52 movies, followed by Bruce Willis in 46 and Samuel L. Jackson in 44 movies

4) Year 2011 had the highest number or release, followed by 2013. The latest year 2015 had 39 releases less than 2011. Although the number of releases are not indicative of the profits made in the corresponding year. It may be a good idea to look at how many of these movie releases actually made profits since that is what matters most

5) Sep month showed the highest number of releases, followed by Dec. Sep - 460 releases, Dec - 415 releases

6) June month saw the highest number of profits, following by Dec

7) The most successful actor of all time who has acted in movies making the highest profit is 'Tom Hanks'. More statistics below. In terms of percentage of movies made profit. Ranked top 3 as below

-Actor Tom Hanks enacted in 34 movies of which 97.0588235294 of the movies made profits¶

-Actor Cameron Diaz enacted in 28 movies of which 96.4285714286 of the movies made profits¶

-Actor Tom Cruise enacted in 33 movies of which 93.9393939394 of the movies made profits¶

8) So for movies to have a higher percentage in terms of earning profits, these casts listed in #7 maybe casted. Well there are other factors which contribute to whether a movie makes profit or not

9) Most successful casts and directors have been identified and if a new movie were to be released with the combination of these set of directors and casts, the probability fo earning good profits is very high, this ofcourse has to be combined with a good story line and the right genre

10) Based on the above findings, we cannot say anything conclusive and the analysis of the current data doesn't indicate with 100% certainity that cast, directors who have been successful will continue to be so. Outcomes can go either ways. The analysis only indicates a higher probability that the most successful directors and casts will continue be successful given that they direct movies of the right genre type that reflect the majority of viewer's taste. This data doesn't account for future changes in viewer's preference for genre type as this is key to a producing a movie that is profitable. For instance we see Drama and Comedy are most preferred of the genre type based on past years. This may change and movies reflecting theses changes are most likely to be profitable. As part of data cleaning, we have also removed records where films haven't earned any revenue and hence the total number of films directed may have been reduced. There are many other factors beyond what has been discussed that may be pivotal in making a movie a success and the inferences made may only be used to find a right mix.
